<subSubSection id="C35436B80B3CFFF3FF18BA1796A9AFE4" lastPageId="47" lastPageNumber="72" pageId="45" pageNumber="70" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B3CFFF1FF18BA179496A802" blockId="45.[136,1451,1792,1850]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3CFFF1FF18BA1796ACA82D" bold="true" box="[136,237,1792,1813]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">
<typeStatus id="54F5DB910B3CFFF1FF18BA1796ACA82D" box="[136,237,1792,1813]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Lectotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
(designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3CFFF1FE1EBA179409A82E" author="Howard, R. A." box="[398,584,1792,1814]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70" refId="ref17132" refString="Howard, R. A. (1989) Flora of the Lesser Antilles, Vol. 5. President and Fellows of Harvard College, Jamaica Plain, Massachusetts, 604 pp." type="book" year="1989">Howard 1989: 411</bibRefCitation>
):— 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3CFFF1FDE5BA179551A82D" author="Dillenius, J. J." box="[629,784,1792,1814]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70" refId="ref16631" refString="Dillenius, J. J. (1732) Hortus elthamensis, vol. 2 [Alter]. Sumptibus auctoris, London, 437 pp." type="book" year="1732">Dillenius (1732</bibRefCitation>
: Fig. 383 on Plate 297, image of the 
<typeStatus id="54F5DB910B3CFFF1FB19BA1792A0A82E" box="[1161,1249,1792,1814]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">lectotype</typeStatus>
available at: https:// bibdigital.rjb.csic.es/viewer/11970/?offset=#page=327).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B3CFFF1FF18BA7E95B8A72B" blockId="45.[136,1452,1897,2067]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3CFFF1FF18BA7E96B0A8BB" bold="true" box="[136,241,1897,1923]" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Notes:—</emphasis>
Once included in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3CFFF1FDA7BA7E94D7A8BB" box="[567,662,1897,1923]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Nopalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="45" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3CFFF1FDA7BA7E94D7A8BB" box="[567,662,1897,1923]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Nopalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this group of hummingbird-pollinated species is now considered to belong in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3CFFF1FF6EBA9A971BA89F" box="[254,346,1933,1959]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="45" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3CFFF1FF6EBA9A971BA89F" box="[254,346,1933,1959]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Opuntia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
once more, based on molecular data. This plant is very widely seen in the Caribbean region as an ornamental but was originally cultivated as a host for the cochineal insect and perhaps too as a medicinal plant (indicated to us by a local resident on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3CFFF1FDBCBAC29483A8D7" box="[556,706,2005,2031]" name="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Saint Vincent</collectingCountry>
but without any specific details). We observed plants in cultivation on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3CFFF1FF3BBAEE9704A72B" box="[171,325,2041,2067]" name="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Saint Vincent</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3CFFF1FEC0BAEE97F3A72B" box="[336,434,2041,2067]" name="Grenada" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Grenada</collectingCountry>
, inhabited islands of 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3CFFF1FD0FBAEE9510A72B" box="[671,849,2041,2067]" name="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">The Grenadines</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3CFFF1FC17BAEE95B5A72B" box="[903,1012,2041,2067]" name="Barbados" pageId="45" pageNumber="70">Barbados</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF3135BB0B3FFFF2FF18BAB69771A8E3" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420395" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5420395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420395/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="71" startId="46.[136,229,1953,1975]" targetBox="[213,1374,190,1929]" targetPageId="46">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B3FFFF2FF18BAB69771A8E3" blockId="46.[136,1452,1953,2011]" pageId="46" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3FFFF2FF18BAB69749A88E" bold="true" box="[136,264,1953,1975]" pageId="46" pageNumber="71">FIGURE 46.</emphasis>
Thin stems of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3FFFF2FE28BAB69471A88E" box="[440,560,1953,1974]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Selenicereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="46" pageNumber="71" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3FFFF2FE28BAB69471A88E" box="[440,560,1953,1974]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="71">Selenicereus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
found on Grenada, tentatively referred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3FFFF2FC50BAB69269A88E" authorityName="Hoxey &amp; Gdaniec" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Rol.-Goss." box="[960,1064,1953,1974]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Selenicereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="46" pageNumber="71" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="plumieri">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3FFFF2FC50BAB69269A88E" box="[960,1064,1953,1974]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="71">S. plumieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
here but without knowledge of the fruits (
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3FFFF2FF00BAD1968CA8E3" box="[144,205,1990,2011]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="71">Hoxey</emphasis>
1698.03).
</paragraph>
</caption>
